<DocsLayout title="Case Studies">

<h1>Case Studies</h1>

<p class="lead">
Real-world zero-day attacks demonstrate how unknown vulnerabilities can have
global consequences. One of the most famous examples is <strong>Stuxnet</strong>.
</p>

<section class="case-study">

<h2>Stuxnet (2010)</h2>

<div class="meta">
  <span>🎯 Target: Industrial Control Systems</span>
  <span>📅 Year: 2010</span>
</div>

<p>
Stuxnet was a highly sophisticated computer worm designed to target Siemens
industrial control systems used in Iran's nuclear program. It exploited
multiple Windows zero-day vulnerabilities, allowing it to spread and execute
without detection.
</p>

<h3>Why It Was Important</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Used multiple zero-day vulnerabilities.</li>
  <li>Targeted physical infrastructure instead of stealing data.</li>
  <li>Changed how governments viewed cyber warfare.</li>
  <li>Became one of the most studied cyberattacks in history.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Lessons Learned</h3>

<div class="lesson-grid">

<div class="lesson">
<h4>Defense in Depth</h4>
<p>Multiple layers of security reduce the impact of unknown vulnerabilities.</p>
</div>

<div class="lesson">
<h4>Regular Updates</h4>
<p>Keeping systems patched reduces the attack surface after fixes are released.</p>
</div>

<div class="lesson">
<h4>Monitoring</h4>
<p>Behavior-based monitoring can detect suspicious activity even when signatures do not.</p>
</div>

</div>

</section>

